05078nam a22007695i 9780231546706DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018007435  a97802315467067 a10.7312/love186562doi  a(DE-B1597)500176  a(OCoLC)1041499821  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aB2430.K654bL68 2018 4aB2430.K654bL68 2018eb 7aBIO0090002bisacsh04a1942231 aLove, Jeff, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Black Circle :bA Life of Alexandre Kojève /cJeff Love. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tINTRODUCTION: A RUSSIAN IN PARIS -- tI. RUSSIAN CONTEXTS -- t1. MADMEN -- t2. THE POSSESSED -- t3. GODMEN -- tII. THE HEGEL LECTURES -- t4. THE LAST REVOLUTION -- t5. TIME NO MORE -- t6 THE BOOK OF THE DEAD -- tIII. THE LATER WRITINGS -- t7. NOBODIES -- t8. ROADS OR RUINS? -- t9. WHY FINALITY? -- tEPILOGUE: THE GRAND INQUISITOR -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlexandre Kojève (1902–1968) was an important and provocative thinker. Born in Russia, he spent most of his life in France. His interpretation of Hegel and his notorious declaration that history had come to an end exerted great influence on French thinkers and writers such as Raymond Aron, Georges Bataille, Maurice Merleau-Ponty, Jacques Lacan, and Raymond Queneau. An unorthodox Marxist, he was a critic of Martin Heidegger and interlocutor of Leo Strauss who played a significant role in establishing the European Economic Community; a polyglot with many unusual interests, he wrote works, mostly unpublished in his lifetime, on quantum physics, the problem of the infinite, Buddhism, atheism, and Vassily Kandinsky’s paintings.In The Black Circle, Jeff Love reinterprets Kojève’s works, showing him to be an essential thinker who challenged modern society and its valuation of individuality, self-interest, and freedom from death. Emphasizing Kojève’s neglected Russian roots, The Black Circle puts him in the context of the late-nineteenth- and early-twentieth-century Russian debates over the proper ends of human life. Love explores notions of perfection, freedom, and finality in Kojève’s account of Hegel and his neglected later works, clarifying Kojève’s emancipatory thinking and the meaning of the oft-misinterpreted “end of history.” Combining intellectual history, close textual analysis, and philosophy, The Black Circle reveals Kojève’s thought as a profound critique of capitalist individualism and a timely meditation on human freedom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aPhilosopherszFrancevBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Philosophers.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060660708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2018 Englishz978311060421408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2018z9783110603217oZDB-23-DPH40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/love1865640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231546706423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231546706/original  a978-3-11-060421-4  EBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060425-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060660-7  Columbia University Press Co